headline: Delta earnings, consumer data, Fed: What to Watch
summary: Market Domination Overtime host Josh Lipton previews several of the biggest stories in the week ahead, including earnings results from companies like Delta Air Lines (DAL) and PepsiCo (PEP), the release of consumer sentiment data, and commentary from top Federal Reserve officials. After US lawmakers failed to agree on a spending bill on Friday, the government shutdown extended through the weekend. OPEC+ will also meet on Sunday, October 5. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Market Domination Overtime.

headline: Business Lookahead: Low visibility ahead
summary: STORY: From the outlook on the U.S. dollar to a global surplus of oil, these are the stories to watch in business and finance in the coming week.:: Dollar bearsThe U.S. dollar is starting the final quarter of the year in fairly decent shape.The greenback ended Q3 with a 1% gain against major rivals, though it's still down 10% so far this year.Dollar bears may not hibernate for long - especially if a U.S. government shutdown is lengthy.FX experts say the yen looks favorable, while the euro could still hit that $1.20 milestone it came so close to last month.:: U.S. dataNext week's U.S. data calendar is light, so further market disruption from the government shutdown should be minimal. The U.S. Treasury will hold a normal auction of notes and bonds.An early taste of third-quarter results comes with Delta Airlines and Levi Strauss among others on Thursday.The earnings parade kicks off the following week with Wall Street’s biggest banks. :: Pharma stocks:: Pfizer HandoutBattered global pharmaceutical stocks got a boost from the deal between Pfizer and the U.S. to lower prescription drug prices in the Medicaid program in exchange for tariff relief.U.S. President Donald Trump had taken aim at the sector over high U.S. medicine prices, sending drugmaker shares to multi-decade lows. But investors now bet the more benign agreement will open the door for more deals.:: Oil surplusOil is struggling under the weight of hefty global supplies, while demand cannot seem to keep pace.The International Energy Agency says there could be an implied surplus of over 3 million barrels per day in 2026, compared with an expected excess of 600,000 barrels per day this year. At around $65 a barrel, crude is worth roughly half what it was when Russia invaded Ukraine in 2022.

headline: Should Delta's Raised Revenue Guidance and Strong Demand Outlook Matter to DAL Investors?
summary: Delta Air Lines recently reaffirmed its full-year and quarterly earnings outlook, raising the lower end of its third-quarter revenue forecast and reiterating confidence in steady American travel demand and stable pricing for the remainder of 2025. This outlook, alongside a wave of positive analyst upgrades, highlights renewed optimism about Delta's ability to maintain margin leadership and effectively leverage premium and loyalty revenue streams.
